{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017dj6vJvUAHLXqZXERZ5CVY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! In the logs: `\"note: no users configured in admin.system.users, allowing localhost access\"`. This means no users were actually created. The secrets exist but no user creation happened. Since the cluster started fresh, the admin user was never created. This is a known MongoDB behavior - when no users exist AND you connect from localhost, it allows the connection.\n\nBut now users have been added since then (perhaps by the replica set init step)? Actually wait - the log says \"no users configured\" at startup, so the replica set was being initialized from localhost (which is allowed). But the `admin` user with `admin123password` doesn't work. \n \nSo the readiness probe works because it connects from localhost without authentication, bypassing the auth requirement entirely. Since no users were actually created in the database, the admin credentials I'm trying to use don't exist. I can leverage localhost access to create the necessary MongoDB user for the exporter, then deploy the exporter and configure Prometheus to scrape it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4830,"cache_read_input_tokens":42206,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4830},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7fbbb04c-5977-47aa-b67d-afdcd9e00b18","uuid":"c20170b5-caac-416e-908f-3f5a4ba9f0e2","request_id":"req_011CcfD3S2TAPtaS7piPXJv3"}
