{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014x5U2H1zz3Cnmz1Rwc3WaK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The MongoDB requires authentication even though the log said \"no users configured... allowing localhost access\". This might mean the replica set has been initialized and users do exist, OR the replica set auth is happening via the keyfile, and the user was created separately.\n\nLet me check by trying different approaches. The `db.adminCommand('ping').ok` works without auth (that's what the readiness probe uses), but replSetGetStatus and users require auth.\n\nActually - when MongoDB is run with `--auth` and with keyfile (`--keyFile`), the behavior is different. The keyfile is for internal cluster auth between replica set members. The localhost exception should still apply for users, BUT only if no users have been created.\n \nSo the fact that `ping` succeeds without credentials but `rs.status()` fails tells me users have definitely been created and the localhost exception no longer applies. The keyfile handles cluster member authentication separately, while user auth is now fully enforced.\n\nThe pods are running and passing readiness checks, so the replica set should already be initialized. Maybe I need to try different credentials or check if the admin user was created with a different username than expected.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":298,"cache_read_input_tokens":47683,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":298},"output_tokens":32,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7fbbb04c-5977-47aa-b67d-afdcd9e00b18","uuid":"a82b7f05-3a5f-4490-8265-c2af21b352b2","request_id":"req_011CcfD52pW1XsGeSpjVY4Za"}
